LA ESCUDERÍA PRESCINDE DE HORNER A PESAR DE SU CONTRATO HASTA 2030🏎

Red Bull Racing vive uno de sus momentos más críticos luego de la destitución de Christian Horner como director del equipo y CEO de la escudería. La noticia, difundida por el diario De Telegraaf y luego confirmada por la Fórmula 1, fue comunicada al personal durante la mañana del miércoles.

Según trascendió, su reemplazo será Laurent Mekies, quien llega desde el equipo satélite Racing Bulls. La decisión habría sido tomada tras una reunión de urgencia entre los copropietarios de Red Bull, Chalerm Yoovidhya y Mark Mateschitz, junto con el director deportivo Oliver Mintzlaff. A pesar de que Horner tenía contrato hasta 2030, la empresa le atribuye parte de responsabilidad por los recientes resultados negativos.

El anuncio llega justo después del Gran Premio de Gran Bretaña, donde Max Verstappen finalizó quinto y Yuki Tsunoda quedó nuevamente fuera de los puntos.

Mintzlaff agradeció públicamente a Horner por sus dos décadas de liderazgo: “Ha sido clave para convertir a Red Bull Racing en uno de los equipos más exitosos y atractivos de la Fórmula 1. Gracias por todo, Christian, siempre serás parte de nuestra historia”. Sin embargo, hasta el momento, Red Bull no ha emitido un comunicado oficial.

El director del equipo Red Bull, Christian Horner, fue despedido después de 20 años en el equipo, dijo un portavoz de la escudería a CNN Sports.

#RedBull no dio un motivo para el despido de Horner, pero le agradeció en un comunicado y agregó que el piloto, de 51 años, “seguirá siendo para siempre una parte importante de la historia de nuestro equipo”.

Durante el tiempo que el británico ha estado al mando, Red Bull ha tenido un éxito tremendo, ganando ocho campeonatos de pilotos y seis de constructores.

🚨 Breaking: Christian Horner’s farewell speech at Milton Keynes has been leaked. His final words as Team Principal and CEO.

Transcript ⬇️
“(Yesterday I was informed) by Red Bull that, operationally, I will no longer be involved with the business or the team moving forward from after this gathering.

“I will still remain employed by the company, but operationally, the baton will be handed over. And that obviously came as a shock to myself, but what I’ve had time to do is to reflect over the last 12 hours or so.

“And I wanted to stand in front of all of you to break this news and just express my gratitude to each and every single member of the team that has given so much during the last 20 and a half years that I’ve been here.

“When I arrived 20 years ago, with a few less grey hairs, I walked into the team, I didn’t know what to expect, but I was immediately welcomed.

“And out of two rundown buildings, we started to build what became a powerhouse in Formula 1. Watching and being part of this team has been the biggest privilege in my life,” Horner concluded.

Thoughts? 💭

SWIPE! ⬅️ Red Bull has made a dramatic mid-season decision, relieving Christian Horner of his position as Team Principal after nearly two decades of leadership that saw eight Drivers’ and six Constructors’ titles. The decision was confirmed in a brief statement celebrating Horner’s “exceptional work” since taking the reins in 2005, but did not specify exact reasons. He reportedly informed staff today at the Milton Keynes base in an emotional farewell, and was succeeded immediately by Laurent Mekies, formerly chief of Red Bull’s junior operation Racing Bulls.

This move arrives amid a turbulent 2025 campaign for Red Bull, plagued by poor car performance that has dropped them to fourth in the Constructors’ standings and heightening internal stress. Speculation around a power struggle, part of the transition to their self-built 2026 power unit program, and ongoing off-track difficulties, linked to cleared allegations of inappropriate behavior from early 2024, appear to have all played a role in the board’s reckoning.

Red Bull will begin the British Grand Prix weekend under Mekies’ leadership, seeking to stabilize its strategy. Meanwhile, Horner’s departure has shaken the F1 paddock, with uncertainty surrounding the future of driver Max Verstappen. His contract reportedly contains performance clauses and with Red Bull underperforming, there are murmurs about potential exits and driver/team realignments in 2026, but the team’s priority now is to regain on-track competitiveness.

Non tutto è per sempre. E Horner ne è la dimostrazione.

Con lui si chiude un ciclo importante. Sotto la sua guida avevano debuttato in F1 nel 2005, e da allora sono arrivati 8 titoli mondiali piloti (2010-2013 con Vettel e 2021-2024 con Verstappen), 6 titoli costruttori (2010-2013 e 2022-2023) e 124 vittorie su 405 GP disputati.

Negli ultimi giorni si è parlato dell’ultimo litigio, in ordine di tempo, tra Jos Verstappen (papà di Max) e appunto l’ormai ex team principal della scuderia di Milton Keynes. E da lì c’è il nodo: cosa cambierà sul mercato piloti? L’addio di Horner porterà Max Verstappen a restare per un altro anno (e magari può essere la ragione per cui rimane), rimandando quindi un effetto domino inevitabile sul mercato, o indurrà l’ormai ex campione in carica a cambiare casacca?

Solo il tempo ce lo dirà e da lì scaturiranno tutte le eventuali interpretazioni della vicenda, tra voci e suggestioni.

With reports of Christian Horner getting a massive £50 million settlement after his sacking from Red Bull Racing on 1 July, many F1 followers are still asking—Why?

With more than five years left on his existing contract, fans want to know why the abrupt curtains on the 51-year-old’s 20-year career at Red Bull, one which saw eight Drivers’ Championships, six Constructors’ titles, and 124 race wins.

Christian Horner is one of the very few names in the paddock that carries a lot of influence, controversy and legacy. Despite never having driven a Formula 1 car, for over a decade and a half, Horner had been the backbone of Red Bull Racing as the team principal, playing a pivotal role in launching and reviving the careers of veteran drivers, giving them a competitive platform at Red Bull.

La giornata di mercoledì 9 luglio 2025 farà indubbiamente parte degli highlights di questa stagione. La notizia dell’improvvisa separazione fra la Red Bull e il suo storico Team Principal Christian Horner ha scosso l’intero paddock della F1 e non solo.

Dopo 20 anni di lavoro e successi, l’uomo che ha sempre guidato la Red Bull non è più al suo posto e a prendere le redini del muretto di Milton Keynes è stato incaricato Laurent Mekies, che sarà anche CEO della squadra. L’ormai ex Team Principal della Racing Bulls, che nella sua avventura precedente aveva ricoperto il ruolo di Direttore Sportivo in Ferrari, ha di fronte a sé l’opportunità più grande della carriera. Ad un giorno di distanza dall’annuncio, i canali Red Bull hanno rilasciato la prima intervista ufficiale di Mekies nel ruolo di Team Principal, dove ha parlato delle sue prime sensazioni e di quali saranno le prime sfide che dovrà affrontare.
